PROJECT PHASES
    PHASE 1 — Fundamentals

        Step 1: Project Setup
            Create a new GitHub repository with a clear README
            Set up a Python virtual environment
            Install core dependencies: langchain, chromadb, openai (or any LLM provider), pypdf, tiktoken
            Create a .env file for API keys and a config.yaml for all settings

        Step 2: Document Ingestion
            Choose your document corpus (e.g., technical docs, research papers, legal contracts)
            Write a document loader that handles at least one format: PDF, markdown, or web pages
            Test that raw text is being extracted correctly before moving on

        Step 3: Chunking
            Implement a text splitter with chunk size: 500–800 tokens and overlap: ~100 tokens
            Print sample chunks to verify boundaries look clean and no sentences are cut awkwardly
            Log the total number of chunks produced from your corpus

        Step 4: Embeddings & Vector Store
            Choose an embedding model (e.g., text-embedding-3-small from OpenAI or a free HuggingFace model)
            Set up ChromaDB or Weaviate locally
            Embed all chunks and store them in the vector store
            Write a simple test query to confirm retrieval is working

        Step 5: Basic Retrieval Pipeline
            Build a function that takes a user query → retrieves top-k chunks → passes them to an LLM → returns an answer
            Make sure the answer includes citations (e.g., document name + page reference)
            Test with 5–10 manual questions from your corpus

        ✅ Phase 1 Deliverable: You can show someone a document, the answer your system produced, and point to the exact source paragraph.

    PHASE 2 — Production Quality
        
        Step 6: Add BM25 Keyword Search
            Install rank_bm25 library
            Build a BM25 index over your chunked documents
            Write a function that retrieves top-k chunks using BM25 alone and test it

        Step 7: Implement Hybrid Retrieval
            Combine BM25 results and vector search results
            Use a simple fusion strategy like Reciprocal Rank Fusion (RRF) to merge the two result sets
            Compare hybrid results vs. vector-only results on a few queries to confirm improvement

        Step 8: Add a Cross-Encoder Re-Ranker
            Install sentence-transformers
            Load a cross-encoder model (e.g., cross-encoder/ms-marco-MiniLM-L-6-v2) or use Cohere's re-rank API
            After hybrid retrieval, pass the query + retrieved chunks through the re-ranker
            Re-order chunks by re-ranker score before sending to the LLM
            Test again and note the difference in result quality

        Step 9: Citation Enforcement
            Add logic so the LLM is explicitly instructed to only answer from retrieved chunks
            If no chunk supports the answer, the system should respond with something like "I don't have enough information to answer this."
            Test with questions that are outside your document corpus to verify refusal works

        Step 10: Version Your Prompts
            Move all prompt templates into a prompts.yaml or prompts.json config file
            Load prompts from this file at runtime instead of hardcoding them in your code
            Commit this file to Git so every prompt change is tracked

        ✅ Phase 2 Deliverable:A hybrid retrieval system with re-ranking and citation enforcement that behaves reliably and refuses to hallucinate.

    PHASE 3 — Production Shippable

        Step 11: Build Your Golden Evaluation Dataset
            Manually write 50–200 question-answer pairs based on your document corpus
            For each pair, note which document/chunk the answer comes from
            Save this as a eval_dataset.json file and commit it to your repo

        Step 12: Write the Evaluation Script
            Install ragas
            Write a script that runs every question in your golden dataset through the full RAG pipeline
            Measure faithfulness (are answers grounded in retrieved chunks?) and answer relevance
            Output a summary report with scores (e.g., faithfulness: 0.87)

        Step 13: Set a Quality Threshold
            Decide on minimum acceptable scores (e.g., faithfulness ≥ 0.80)
            Make your evaluation script exit with a non-zero code if scores fall below the threshold

        Step 14: Wire Into CI Pipeline
            Set up GitHub Actions (free)
            Create a workflow file .github/workflows/eval.yml that runs your evaluation script on every pull request
            If the eval fails, the PR is blocked from merging
            Test this by intentionally breaking a prompt and confirming the build fails

        Step 15: Final Documentation
            Write a thorough README covering: what the system does, how to run it, your tech stack, and your eval results
            Include a diagram of the full pipeline (ingestion → chunking → hybrid retrieval → re-ranking → LLM → cited answer)
            Add a section on lessons learned and what you'd improve next

        ✅ Phase 3 Deliverable: A fully evaluated, CI-gated RAG system with versioned prompts that behaves like a real production AI system.

